Description: neutralise Build.sh's compile-time-assert macro
 Build.sh probes the target with a struct full of compile-time assertions, each
 declaring `char name[(assertion) ? 1 : -1]` so that a false assertion is a
 negative array size and fails the compile. GCC bug 55009 makes gcc reject that
 construct even when the assertion holds, so the probe fails for reasons that
 have nothing to do with the target and Build.sh aborts. Drop the array bound:
 the assertions are re-checked properly by the real build.
Origin: vendor, shell-versions
Bug: https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=55009
Forwarded: not-needed

--- Build.sh
+++ Build.sh
@@ -1856,7 +1856,7 @@
 	#define CHAR_BIT 8	/* defuse this test on really legacy systems */
 	#endif
 	struct ctasserts {
-	#define cta(name, assertion) char name[(assertion) ? 1 : -1]
+	#define cta(name, assertion) char name /* shvr: neutralised (gcc bug 55009) */
 /* this one should be defined by the standard */
 cta(char_is_1_char, (sizeof(char) == 1) && (sizeof(signed char) == 1) &&
     (sizeof(unsigned char) == 1));
